2 SENATE BILL 941
1 (a) (1) In this section the following words have the meanings indicated.
2 (2) “Office” means the Office of Tenant and Landlord Affairs in the
3 Department of Housing and Community Development.
4 (3) (i) “Severe health and safety risk property” means a rental property
5 that routinely fails to meet basic health and safety standards.
6 (ii) “Severe health and safety risk property” includes:
7 1. a rental property that is in continued noncompliance with
8 local housing codes, resulting in chronic unsafe housing conditions;
9 2. a severely distressed rental property;
10 3. a rental property that has repeated cycles of violations,
11 citations, and failures to remediate; and
12 4. a persistently hazardous rental property.
13 (b) This section applies only to properties with 50 or more units.
14 (c) It is the intent of the General Assembly that the Office focus on the most severe,
15 serious, and high–volume violations and that the planned interventions be limited to the
16 most severe health and safety risk properties.
17 (d) (1) The Office, in collaboration with the Attorney General, shall develop a
18 plan to:
19 (1) (i) identify severe health and safety risk properties in the State;
20 (2) (ii) expand the structure of the Office to address severe health and
21 safety risk properties in the State; and
22 (3) (iii) provide effective interventions to mitigate predatory,
23 noncompliant, and negligent landlords of multi–unit rental properties in the State.
24 (2) The Office shall communicate and coordinate with counties and
25 municipalities in interventions and identify ways to leverage county resources.
26 (3) The Office shall seek input from renters, renter advocates, property
27 owners, housing providers, housing associations, and other stakeholders to develop the plan
28 required under paragraph (1) of this subsection.
29 (c) (e) The plan required under subsection (b) (d) of this section shall:

SENATE BILL 941 3
1 (1) create a process for identifying:
2 (i) severe health and safety properties; and
3 (ii) predatory landlord practices;
4 (2) develop methods for the referral of properties to the Office, including:
5 (i) by residents that currently live in a property;
6 (ii) through coordination with municipal and county agencies;
7 (iii) by tenant associations; and
8 (iv) by other organizations that serve renters and communities;
9 (3) determine appropriate interventions to protect the health and safety of
10 residents living in severe health and safety risk properties, including:
11 (i) financial consequences, fines, and liability for investigation and
12 intervention costs;
13 (ii) legal interventions such as injunctions and legal proceedings;
14 (iii) required tenant escrow;
15 (iv) the issuance of corrective action plans with deadlines;
16 (v) mandatory follow–up inspections;
17 (vi) required timelines for addressing violations;
18 (vii) mandatory pest eradication plans;
19 (viii) structural repair requirements;
20 (ix) temporary relocation plans for tenants in units that are unsafe
21 for occupancy;
22 (x) requirements for landlords to submit remediation plans and
23 records of completed repairs; and
24 (xi) any other mitigations; and
25 (4) identify costs and options for containing costs, including leveraging
26 collaboration with the county or local housing agency and the utilization of county inspectors
27 versus the hiring of State inspectors; and

4 SENATE BILL 941
1 (5) make recommendations for statutory changes to provide effective
2 mitigation and relief for tenants.
3 (d) (f) (1) On or before August 31, 2027, the Department of Housing and
4 Community Development shall submit the plan and recommendations developed under this
5 section to the Governor and, in accordance with § 2–1257 of the State Government Article,
6 the General Assembly.
7 (2) On or before December 31, 2027, the Department of Housing and
8 Community Development shall submit a report to the Governor and, in accordance with §
9 2–1257 of the State Government Article, the General Assembly that includes:
10 (i) the properties identified under subsection (d) of this section;
11 (ii) the types of violations identified;
12 (iii) the reason a property is included in the plan required under
13 subsection (d) of this section;
14 (iv) any interventions undertaken and the status of violations as a
15 result of the plan; and
16 (v) any other helpful information.
17 (g) The Department of Housing and Community Development shall publish the
18 list of severe health and safety risk properties, including the names of properties, publicly on
19 the Department’s website.
20 SECTION 2. AND BE IT FURTHER ENACTED, That this Act shall take effect July
21 1, 2026. It shall remain effective for a period of 1 year and 6 months and, at the end of
22 December 31, 2027, this Act, with no further action required by the General Assembly, shall
23 be abrogated and of no further force and effect.
Approved:
